docs.abstract: A plan to revive U.S. chip manufacturing rests partly on a company that is firing workers and delaying factories, even as the government pushes for the opposite.
docs.snippet: A plan to revive U.S. chip manufacturing rests partly on a company that is firing workers and delaying factories, even as the government pushes for the opposite.
docs.lead_paragraph: At an annual gathering of tech executives and billionaires in Sun Valley, Idaho, this past July, Gina Raimondo commandeered a table near a duck pond and tried to exert her influence as the U.S. secretary of commerce to help rescue an ailing national champion.

headline.main: The White House Bet Big on Intel. Will It Backfire?
headline.print_headline: Will the White House’s Big Bet on Intel Backfire?

byline.original: By Ana Swanson and Tripp Mickle

docs.abstract: Intel was for decades Silicon Valley’s dominant chip company. But missed opportunities and poor execution left it on the sidelines in tech’s latest gold rush.
docs.snippet: Intel was for decades Silicon Valley’s dominant chip company. But missed opportunities and poor execution left it on the sidelines in tech’s latest gold rush.
docs.lead_paragraph: In 2005, there was no inkling of the artificial intelligence boom that would come years later. But directors at Intel, whose chips served as electronic brains in most computers, faced a decision that might have altered how that transformative technology evolved.

headline.main: How Intel Got Left Behind in the A.I. Chip Boom
headline.print_headline: After Setbacks And Job Cuts, Intel’s Future  In State of Flux

byline.original: By Steve Lohr and Don Clark
